  "prompt": "Can it be too cold to snow?",
  "response": "Yes, it can be too cold to snow. While this might seem counterintuitive, snow typically forms when temperatures are at or near freezing (32\u00b0F or 0\u00b0C). When temperatures drop significantly below freezing, the air becomes too dry to produce snow. This is because cold air holds very little moisture, and snow requires some moisture to form. Generally, snow is most likely to occur when temperatures are between 28\u00b0F and 35\u00b0F (-2\u00b0C to 2\u00b0C). Very cold, dry air cannot produce snowfall.",
